06797nam a22010335i 9780228014775DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280147757 a10.1515/97802280147752doi  a(DE-B1597)658117  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKEQ740b.W75 2023 7aLAW0180002bisacsh04a342.71402/922302aA Written Constitution for Quebec? /ced. by Richard Albert, Léonid Sirota. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b4 figures, 5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDemocracy, Diversity, and Citizen Engagement Series00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Constitution and Codification -- tFraming the Debate -- tOui, Quebec Needs a Written Constitution -- tLegal Roadblocks to Proposals for a Quebec Constitution -- tFormal Constitutions of the Federating and Federated States of Canada -- tPurposes and Prospects -- tA Codified Quebec Constitution: A Vain Pursuit or the Making of a Sovereign People? -- tInterculturalism and the Plea for an Informal Constitution: Responding to the Challenge of Polyethnicity in Quebec -- tConstitutive Power and the Nation(s) of Quebec -- tWhy Alberta Needs a Constitution -- tInsights from Abroad -- tPolitical Functions and Limitations of Contemporary State Constitutions in the United States -- tThe Brazilian Experience with Subnational Constitutions: What Went Wrong? -- tConstitutionalization à l’Écosse: Subnational Constitutionalism as Constitutional Reconciliation -- tShould Quebec Adopt a Written Constitution? A (But Not The) Conclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNo province in Canada has codified a written constitution, and whether Quebec should be the first remains a controversial question. A Written Constitution for Quebec? enters into the debate, drawing a roadmap through the legal, political, and constitutional terrain of the issue. Leading scholars each take their own position in the debate, examining the issue from various sides and exploring the forms and limits of a codified Quebec constitution by asking whether Quebec should adopt a written constitution, how the province might go about it, and what such a document might achieve. Along with a comprehensive introduction to constitutional codification and how it relates to Quebec, the book opens with a proposal for a written constitution, with the analyses that follow expressing a diversity of views on the feasibility and desirability of a written constitution for the province. An array of perspectives through the lenses of Indigenous inclusion and reconciliation, interculturalism and democratic constitutionalism, and insights from other federal and plurinational states – are included in this wide-ranging volume. Taking a doctrinal, historical, theoretical, and comparative approach, A Written Constitution for Quebec? extensively addresses Quebec’s constitutional future in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConstitutional historyzQuébec (Province). 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh  a1867.  aAct 1982.  aAlberta.  aBrazil.  aCanadian.  aNational Assembly.  aScotland.  aUnited Kingdom.  aUnited States.  acodification.  acodified.  aconstituent power.  aconstitutionalism.  aconstitutionmaking.  adistinct society.  afederalism.  aformal.  aidentity.  ainformal.  ainterculturalism.  anation.  anationhood.  apluralism.  apolitics.  apolyethnicity.  aprovincial.  asovereignty.  asubnational.  asubstate.1 aAlbert, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca